{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"71baa7be-0ebe-428a-b0a5-326f393bb568","content":"## Collecting a CPU Trace on Windows (.NET 8)\n\n**Best tool: `dotnet-trace`** (lightweight, .NET-specific, no install beyond the global tool).\n\n### Quick steps\n\n```powershell\n# 1 – Install the tool (one-time)\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n\n# 2 – Find your process ID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# 3 – Collect a CPU-sampling trace (default ~1 kHz)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** (Diagnostics → Open Trace) or convert to `.speedscope.json`:\n\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace convert <file>.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\n\n### Alternatives worth knowing\n\n| Tool | When to prefer it |\n|---|---|\n| **PerfView** | Need OS-level ETW events, GC details, or kernel stacks |\n| **dotnet-counters** | Quick live triage before committing to a full trace |\n\n> **Tip:** If the service is so pegged you can't attach, use `PerfView /nogui collect` — it hooks at the OS level and handles high-CPU scenarios more reliably.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"dfb60716-d531-4993-b0d0-12651f9031ae","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a knowledge question - no code changes or file operations needed.","outputTokens":368,"requestId":"D81F:1D44F2:836265:97541D:69FBEA3E"},"id":"6c71bb47-9053-4326-9fbc-244123ff4acb","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:26:33.318Z","parentId":"2d6b5c96-c4a0-4bcc-a1e6-e823fc05e7dd"}
